A square has a diagonal of length $10\sqrt{2}$ centimeters. What is the number of square centimeters in the area of the square?
inference:
**Solution**

The diagonal of a square divides the square into two congruent right triangles.

The length of each side of the square is the hypotenuse of one of these right triangles.

Therefore, each side of the square is $\frac{10\sqrt{2}}{2} = 5\sqrt{2}$ centimeters.

The area of the square is the square of the length of one side:

$$Area = (5\sqrt{2})^2 = 25 \cdot 2 = 50 \text{ square centimeters}$$

**Final Answer: $\boxed{50}$. I hope it is correct.**
ground_truth: A diagonal of a square divides the square into two 45-45-90 right triangles, so the side length of the square is $10\sqrt{2}/\sqrt{2}=10$ centimeters and its area is $10^2=\boxed{100}$ square centimeters
